      { question: "After giving insulin 10 units IV with D50W for hyperkalemia, what is the critical monitoring requirement?", options: ["Serum calcium every 30 minutes","Blood glucose every 1 hour for 4-6 hours (hypoglycemia risk)","Continuous pulse oximetry","Hourly neurological checks"], correct: 1, rationale: "Insulin-induced hypoglycemia occurs in up to 75% of patients and can be delayed up to 4-6 hours. Blood glucose monitoring every hour is mandatory. D50W must be co-administered and may need repeated dosing." },
      { question: "A CKD patient on lisinopril develops chronic K+ of 5.8. What is the preferred management approach?", options: ["Discontinue lisinopril permanently","Add patiromer or sodium zirconium cyclosilicate to enable continued ACEi therapy","Switch to amlodipine and stop all RAAS inhibitors","Start furosemide 80 mg daily"], correct: 1, rationale: "Adding a potassium binder to enable continued ACEi/ARB therapy is preferred because RAAS inhibitors provide critical renal and cardiovascular protection in CKD. Newer binders (patiromer, SZC) are well-tolerated for chronic use." }
